# Frontend Development Standards

## When This Rule Applies

When working in `src/frontend/` directory with React components, hooks, or styles.

---

## Core Requirements

### Component Structure
- Use functional components with TypeScript
- Props interface at top of file
- Component as named export (not default export)
- Styles with Tailwind CSS or CSS modules

### File Organization
- One component per file
- Co-locate tests with components (`ComponentName.test.tsx`)
- Hooks in dedicated `hooks/` directory
- Utilities in `utils/` directory

### Naming Conventions
- **Components:** PascalCase (e.g., `UserProfile.tsx`)
- **Hooks:** camelCase with `use` prefix (e.g., `useAuth.ts`)
- **Utilities:** camelCase (e.g., `formatDate.ts`)
- **Types:** PascalCase with `Props` or `Type` suffix (e.g., `UserCardProps`)

---

## Examples

### Good Component

```tsx
interface UserCardProps {
  name: string;
  email: string;
  onEdit?: () => void;
}

export function UserCard({ name, email, onEdit }: UserCardProps) {
  return (
    <div className="p-4 border rounded shadow-sm">
      <h3 className="text-lg font-bold">{name}</h3>
      <p className="text-gray-600">{email}</p>
      {onEdit && (
        <button onClick={onEdit} className="mt-2 text-blue-500">
          Edit
        </button>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Bad Component

```tsx
